#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:1
msgid "A basic module"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:3
msgid "What is a module?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:5
msgid ""
"A module is a function that takes an attribute set and returns an attribute "
"set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:6
msgid ""
"It may declare options, telling which attributes are allowed in the final "
"outcome."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:7
msgid "It may define values, for options declared by itself or other modules."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:8
msgid ""
"When evaluated by the module system, it produces an attribute set based on "
"the declarations and definitions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:10
msgid ""
"The simplest possible module is a function that takes any attributes and "
"returns an empty attribute set:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:12
#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:26
msgid "options.nix"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:12
msgid ""
"{ ... }:\n"
"{\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:19
msgid ""
"To define any values, the module system first has to know which ones are "
"allowed. This is done by declaring *options* that specify which attributes "
"can be set and used elsewhere."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:22
msgid "Declaring options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:24
msgid ""
"Options are declared under the top-level `options` attribute with [`lib."
"mkOption`](https://nixos.org/manual/nixpkgs/stable/#function-library-lib."
"options.mkOption)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:26
msgid ""
"{ lib, ... }:\n"
"{\n"
"  options = {\n"
"    name = lib.mkOption { type = lib.types.str; };\n"
"  };\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:32
msgid ""
"The `lib` argument is passed automatically by the module system. This makes "
"[Nixpkgs library functions](https://nixos.org/manual/nixpkgs/stable/#chap-"
"functions) available in each module's function body."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:35
msgid ""
"The ellipsis `...` is necessary because the module system can pass arbitrary "
"arguments to modules."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:39
msgid ""
"The attribute `type` in the argument to `lib.mkOption` specifies which "
"values are valid for an option. There are several types available under "
"[`lib.types`](https://nixos.org/manual/nixos/stable/#sec-option-types-basic)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:42
msgid ""
"Here we have declared an option `name` of type `str`: The module system will "
"expect a string when a value is defined."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:45
msgid ""
"Now that we have declared an option, we would naturally want to give it a "
"value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:47
msgid "Defining values"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:49
msgid "Options are set or *defined* under the top-level `config` attribute:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:51
msgid "config.nix"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:51
msgid ""
"{ ... }:\n"
"{\n"
"  config = {\n"
"    name = \"Boaty McBoatface\";\n"
"  };\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:56
msgid ""
"In our option declaration, we created an option `name` with a string type. "
"Here, in our option definition, we have set that same option to a string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:59
msgid ""
"Option declarations and option definitions don't need to be in the same "
"file. Which modules will contribute to the resulting attribute set is "
"specified when setting up module system evaluation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:62
msgid "Evaluating modules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:64
msgid ""
"Modules are evaluated by [`lib.evalModules`](https://nixos.org/manual/"
"nixpkgs/stable/#module-system-lib-evalModules) from the Nixpkgs library. It "
"takes an attribute set as an argument, where the `modules` attribute is a "
"list of modules to merge and evaluate."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:67
msgid ""
"The output of `evalModules` contains information about all evaluated "
"modules, and the final values appear in the attribute `config`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:69
msgid "default.nix"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:69
msgid ""
"let\n"
"  pkgs = import <nixpkgs> { };\n"
"  result = pkgs.lib.evalModules {\n"
"    modules = [\n"
"      ./options.nix\n"
"      ./config.nix\n"
"    ];\n"
"  };\n"
"in\n"
"result.config\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:74
msgid ""
"Here's a helper script to parse and evaluate our `default.nix` file with "
"[`nix-instantiate --eval`](https://nix.dev/manual/nix/stable/command-ref/nix-"
"instantiate) and print the output as JSON:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:76
msgid "eval.bash"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:76
msgid "nix-shell -p jq --run \"nix-instantiate --eval --json --strict | jq\"\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:81
msgid ""
"As long as every definition has a corresponding declaration, evaluation will "
"be successful. If there is an option definition that has not been declared, "
"or the defined value has the wrong type, the module system will throw an "
"error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:84
msgid ""
"Running the script (`./eval.bash`) should show an output that matches what "
"we have configured:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../tutorials/module-system/a-basic-module/index.md:86
msgid ""
"{\n"
"  \"name\": \"Boaty McBoatface\"\n"
"}"
msgstr ""
